    <text type="letter">  
        <body>    
            <pb xml:id="leaf001r" facs="loc.01095.001_large.jpg" type="recto"/>
            <opener>  
                <dateline>
                    <name type="place">Cambridge, Mass</name>
                    <name type="place">5 De Wolf st</name>
                    <date when="1889-05-12">May 12<ptr target="loc.01095_n1"/></date>
                </dateline>
                <salute> Dr. Mr. Whitman&#8212;</salute>
            </opener>
            <p>Our literary people are all agog over Mr. Howell's<ptr target="n0316"/> attempted
                dethronement of Scott,<ptr target="n4277"/> and the preference which he assigns to
                    Tolstoi<ptr target="loc.01095_n3"/> over the "Wizard of the North.<ptr
                    target="loc.01095_n2"/> Mr. Howell's has used a portion of your general
                indictment of all the old-world literatures viz that they are saturated in the 
                <pb xml:id="leaf001v" facs="loc.01095.002_large.jpg" type="verso"/> 
                <pb xml:id="leaf002r" facs="loc.01095.003_large.jpg" type="recto"/>
            aristocratic spirit&#8212;and lack that enthusiasum for democracy which the coming
                literature must have. Could you not give the public your views on the subject which
                is now cleaving literary Boston in twain? If you would not do this would you be so
                kind as to give me your private view&#8212;I would not publish it if you so desired.
                If you desired to submit    
                <pb xml:id="leaf002v" facs="loc.01095.004_large.jpg" type="verso"/>
                <pb xml:id="leaf003r" facs="loc.01095.005_large.jpg"
                    type="recto"/>
            a ms. on the subject to the papers or magazines here I would be glad to present it
                for you and would get you the best possible terms. You do not now remember
                me&#8212;I therefore give as references&#8212;Mr A. H. Stephenson<ptr target="loc.01095_n4"
                /> 214 Chestnut St Philadelphia&#8212;or Rev. Dr. A. A. Livermore<ptr target="loc.01095_n5"
                /> Meadville, Pa.</p> 
            <closer>
                <salute> Very Sincerely </salute>
                <signed rend="right"><hi rend="underline">John B. Barnhill.</hi></signed>
            </closer>
